My comment is based more on the events that led to the need for the service call rather than the service call itself.  Back in February or March of 2017, I discovered that one of my panels was not working.  I discovered this when I called because my system was not communicating properly.  A service appointent was scheduled for several weeks from that date.  A technician came out, but said he was unable to complete the repair because it was a 2-tech job.  Another appointment was scheduled for about 6 weeks later.  That appointment had to be cancelled due to weather, and was rescheduled for me for a date that was not convenient for me, about 2 months later.  I encountered many difficulties in trying to reschedule; the details should be in my file, as I made numerous calls to your customer service department.  The repair was finally completed in August.  My complaint is not only with the length of time it took to complete the repair, but with the difficulty in getting information.  It turns out that the repair did not require 2 techs; the person who originally scheduled the repair put in wrong information, and it took several months and several inquiries from me to get someone to discover the real problem.  Additionally, each time I called I got a different person, who gave me different information.  One time I called and someone from customer service was trying to schedule the service appointment, couldn't get someone one the phone so sent an email.  When I hadn't heard back after about a week and called again, I was told that the person who would be the one to schedule the appointment was on vacation and that's why nothing had been done.   Was there no one covering for that person?  I could go one, but the notes of my phone calls should be in my file; at least that is what I was told.  The bottom line is it was quite frustrating as a customer to have to speak to a different person every time, and to get different information with each phone call. Everyone I spoke to was very pleasant, and tried to help me, but it seemed that there was a lack of communication within the company-the left hand didn't know what the right hand was doing so to speak.  Perhaps if there had been one person in charge of my account the problem could have been solved more quickly, and I would have been given consistent accurate information about the status of my repair.

When the panels were installed, we were told that maintenance, including cleaning, is the responsibility of Vivint Solar.  However, a year later, several requests to look at the placement of the panels and also requests for maintenance service, have been either ignored or blown off by local reps.  The most recent service call was completely and totally unnecessary.  There is nothing wrong with our panes EXCEPT that they have not been maintained.  Yet a technician spent hours here replacing perfectly good parts, even admitting that the service was pointless!!  I have been told to just "wash them with a power washer."  Well, I don't have a power washer.  Being a good sport, and up on the ladder to clean gutters in any case, I did try to clean the lower panels myself using a hose nozzle.  Unfortunately, the built up dirt and leaf decay was NOT responsive to the spray.  Now, if Vivint can afford to pay a technician to replace non-defective parts, why can't they send someone to maintain the panels properly so that they work??!!??  I don't have the equipment, knowledge, or tools to properly clean the panels, not to mention that I have no interest in climbing around on the roof!!
